{
  "name": "Anxiety",
  "remarks": [
    "Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) in the general population.",
    "",
    "Prevalence: lifetime prevalence of GAD is roughly 6-10% in US samples and about twice as ",
    "high in women as in men, with onset spread from adolescence through middle age. Sources: ",
    "Kessler RC et al. 'Lifetime prevalence and age-of-onset distributions of DSM-IV disorders ",
    "in the National Comorbidity Survey Replication.' Arch Gen Psychiatry. 2005;62(6):593-602 ",
    "(lifetime GAD 5.7%, median onset age 31). ",
    "Ruscio AM et al. 'Cross-sectional Comparison of the Epidemiology of DSM-5 Generalized ",
    "Anxiety Disorder Across the Globe.' JAMA Psychiatry. 2017;74(5):465-475 (US lifetime ",
    "prevalence 7.8%; F:M roughly 2:1).",
    "",
    "Onset is modeled as an annual-probability loop from age 12 to age 55. Female annual ",
    "hazard 0.0022 over ~43 at-risk years yields lifetime risk of about 9%; male annual hazard ",
    "0.0011 yields about 4.6% (overall ~7%). A lifetime history of depression (the 'depression' ",
    "attribute set by the depression module, or 'mdd' set by veteran_mdd) raises the hazard ",
    "about 2.5x, reflecting the strong observed MDD-GAD comorbidity (Kessler RC et al., ",
    "'The epidemiology of generalized anxiety disorder', Psychiatr Clin North Am. 2001).",
    "",
    "Diagnosis: GAD-7 assessment (LOINC 70274-6, reused from encounter/anxiety_screening) at an ",
    "ambulatory symptom encounter; ConditionOnset uses SNOMED-CT 21897009 'Generalized anxiety ",
    "disorder (disorder)' (no other module in this repo codes GAD).",
    "",
    "Treatment: mental health care plan with cognitive-behavioral therapy for everyone; 45% ",
    "also receive first-line escitalopram, 25% buspirone, and 30% are managed with therapy ",
    "alone. Long-term benzodiazepines are deliberately not modeled. About 30% of medicated ",
    "patients fail the first agent and are switched to sertraline. During maintenance, 12% per ",
    "quarter discontinue their medication without medical advice (non-adherence); most later ",
    "resume care at a follow-up visit. Remission occurs with probability 0.25 per quarter on ",
    "medication (0.30 per quarter in the therapy-only arm); medication is continued 3-6 months ",
    "after remission before discontinuation.",
    "",
    "Relapse: GAD is chronic-relapsing; remitted patients face a 5%/year relapse hazard vs a ",
    "5%/year chance of durable recovery (~50% eventually relapse; Yonkers KA et al., 'Phenomenology ",
    "and course of generalised anxiety disorder', Br J Psychiatry. 1996). Relapse is detected ",
    "via GAD-7 at a scheduled wellness encounter.",
    "",
    "Attributes: sets 'anxiety' = true at first onset and intentionally KEEPS it true after ",
    "remission as a lifetime history marker for other modules (mirrors the depression module). ",
    "The currently-active condition is tracked via 'anxiety_condition' (ended in remission). ",
    "Also uses 'anxiety_careplan' and 'anxiety_med' internally; 'anxiety_med' is cleared (set ",
    "to nil) whenever medication is stopped without an immediate replacement, so the shared ",
    "EncounterEnd can route therapy-only patients correctly on repeat episodes.",
    "",
    "Codes reused from existing modules: LOINC 70274-6 (encounter/anxiety_screening), SNOMED ",
    "encounter/care plan/activity codes (veteran_mdd, attention_deficit_disorder, gout), ",
    "RxNorm 312938 sertraline (veteran_ptsd). Verified against RxNav: 349332 escitalopram ",
    "10 MG Oral Tablet, 866083 buspirone hydrochloride 10 MG Oral Tablet."
  ],
